22
00:01:12,880 --> 00:01:16,140
All right, it's time for level one of our
friendship quest.

23
00:01:16,140 --> 00:01:19,080
We're kicking things off with the most
important question of all,

24
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:21,840
asking about the person you're actually
talking to.

25
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:24,800
This is where we master the classic, do
you.

26
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:29,320
It's simple, it's direct, and trust me, it
works every single time.

27
00:01:29,320 --> 00:01:33,280
Let's use an example. So imagine you ask
someone, do you like sushi?

28
00:01:33,280 --> 00:01:36,280
If they do, they'll say, yes, I do, pretty
simple.

29
00:01:36,280 --> 00:01:38,600
If they don't, they'll say, no, I don't.

30
00:01:38,600 --> 00:01:41,920
See how the answer uses the same word you
started the question with?

31
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:45,920
It's like a perfect little echo, do gets
you do or don't.

32
00:01:45,920 --> 00:01:50,040
Okay, now what's really interesting here
is the difference between do not and

33
00:01:50,040 --> 00:01:53,240
don't. I mean, no, I do not is totally
correct,

34
00:01:53,240 --> 00:01:55,040
but it sounds a bit formal, right?

35
00:01:55,040 --> 00:01:56,520
Kind of like you're writing an essay.

36
00:01:56,520 --> 00:01:59,040
When you're just chatting with friends,
especially in America,

37
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:02,240
you're almost always gonna hear the
contraction, no, I don't.

38
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:04,260
It's just quicker, way more casual,

39
00:02:04,260 --> 00:02:06,860
and it'll make you sound supernatural.

40
00:02:06,860 --> 00:02:09,400
Okay, so you've totally mastered asking
about you.

41
00:02:09,400 --> 00:02:10,960
It's time for level two.

42
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:13,180
This is where conversations get really
