43
00:02:13,180 --> 00:02:15,280
because you can start asking about other
people,

44
00:02:15,280 --> 00:02:18,320
like your friend's brother or their
favorite teacher, anyone.

45
00:02:18,320 --> 00:02:22,080
And for that, we need a new magic word,
does.

46
00:02:22,080 --> 00:02:26,280
So let's start with a really simple
statement. He sings well.

47
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:30,320
See that little S on the end of sings?
That S is the key.

48
00:02:30,320 --> 00:02:31,840
It's a signal that we're talking about

49
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:35,000
just one other person, a he or a she.

50
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:38,320
Now get ready because we're about to flip
this into a question.

51
00:02:38,320 --> 00:02:41,440
But watch out, here's a super common
mistake.

52
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:44,360
A lot of people might say, does he sings
well?

53
00:02:44,360 --> 00:02:48,680
It kind of seems logical, right? But in
English, this is a total trap.

54
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:51,680
We've gotta fix this to ask the question
the right way.

55
00:02:51,680 --> 00:02:56,000
And here is the secret. Does he sing well?
So where did the S go?

56
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,440
Okay, think of does as a superhero.

57
00:02:58,440 --> 00:03:01,780
It flies in and it grabs the S from the
verb sing.

58
00:03:01,780 --> 00:03:04,480
So since does is now carrying the S,

59
00:03:04,480 --> 00:03:08,780
the main verb sing gets to just go back to
its simple original form.

60
00:03:08,780 --> 00:03:12,020
Just remember this rule. When the
superhero does appears,

61
00:03:12,020 --> 00:03:14,600
the next verb never has an S.

62
00:03:14,600 --> 00:03:17,000
You know, to make this even easier to
remember,

63
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:18,960
let's think of it as two different teams.

64
00:03:18,960 --> 00:03:22,000
On the do team, we've got I, you, we, and
they.

65
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,800
For anyone on that team, you use do.

66
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:28,920
But on the does team, we have the special
players, he, she, and it.

67
00:03:28,920 --> 00:03:33,520
And this also includes any single person's
name, like John or Emily.

68
00:03:33,520 --> 00:03:37,600
For anyone on this team, you always,
always use does.

69
00:03:37,600 --> 00:03:41,160
And this shows a great pro tip for
sounding like a native speaker.

70
00:03:41,160 --> 00:03:44,440
When you ask a question like, does John
have a bike?

71
00:03:44,440 --> 00:03:47,880
The most natural answer isn't yes, John
does.

72
00:03:47,880 --> 00:03:51,680
Instead, you swap the name for the
pronoun. Yes, he does.

73
00:03:51,680 --> 00:03:53,160
It's such a small change,

74
00:03:53,160 --> 00:03:56,720
but it makes a huge difference in how
natural you sound.

75
00:03:56,720 --> 00:04:00,360
Okay, let's broaden our conversation
skills a little more.

76
00:04:00,360 --> 00:04:02,880
What if you wanna ask about a whole group
of people,

77
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:05,600
like your friend's family or your favorite
band?

78
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:08,040
Well, this is where we bring back our old
friend,

79
00:04:08,040 --> 00:04:12,080
Do, to ask about they. And the best part?

80
00:04:12,080 --> 00:04:16,280
The pattern is exactly the same as DU.
It's super, super easy.

81
00:04:16,280 --> 00:04:18,000
If you ask, do they sing well?

82
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:21,400
The answer is simply, yes they do, or no
they don't.

83
00:04:21,400 --> 00:04:23,200
Perfect for asking about a sports team

84
00:04:23,200 --> 00:04:26,920
or, you know, your favorite singers. And
here's another quick tip.

85
00:04:26,920 --> 00:04:29,200
If you're talking about two or more people
by name,

86
00:04:29,200 --> 00:04:32,280
like in the question, do John and Paul
play the guitar?

87
00:04:32,280 --> 00:04:34,880
In your answer, those names just become
they.

88
00:04:34,880 --> 00:04:37,120
So you'd say, yes, they do.

89
00:04:37,120 --> 00:04:41,080
This works for any combo of two or more
people. Simple as that.

